Thomas likes it, don't you?

230
00:19:16,721 --> 00:19:20,282
No, you don't. No.
I knew you didn't.

231
00:19:20,358 --> 00:19:22,724
- Honey, when do we eat?
- Hey, man!

232
00:19:22,794 --> 00:19:24,728
- As soon as it's ready.
- Relax, okay, Papa?

233
00:19:24,796 --> 00:19:27,060
I'm hoping to come back
with all my parts.

234
00:19:27,132 --> 00:19:29,566
[Baby Talk Continues]

235
00:19:34,839 --> 00:19:37,740
[Grunts, Groans]

236
00:19:37,809 --> 00:19:40,039
- Again?
- At least twice a week.

237
00:19:40,111 --> 00:19:42,705
Hey, I know what
the limit is, okay?

238
00:19:42,781 --> 00:19:44,908
I just think we oughta
test it once in a while.

239
00:19:44,983 --> 00:19:48,077
I mean they gotta let us get away
from this tyke sometime.

240
00:19:48,153 --> 00:19:52,283
Could be worse. At least we're
with a good cookie boy like Thomas.

241
00:19:52,357 --> 00:19:54,587
- Cookie boy.
- You're a cookie boy.

242
00:19:56,661 --> 00:19:58,925
[Gurgling]

243
00:19:58,997 --> 00:20:03,093
Guess he's off to laugh
at the kitchen now, huh?

244
00:20:03,168 --> 00:20:05,898
Buy him all these toys,
he laughs at the walls.

245
00:20:07,806 --> 00:20:09,933
Doesn't this bother you guys?

246
00:20:10,008 --> 00:20:12,238
How long are we gonna
be dragged around like this?

247
00:20:12,310 --> 00:20:16,007
Hasn't happened to me.
I'm not over there runnin' into walls.

248
00:20:16,081 --> 00:20:18,572
- I'm just trying to test the envelope.
- You oughta test your I.Q.

249
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:23,349
- [Thomas] Hug-a-bug.
- What is that? "Hug-a-bug?"

250
00:20:23,421 --> 00:20:26,948
- Where'd he get that?
- I thought you taught it to him.

251
00:20:27,025 --> 00:20:29,459
[Thomas]
Hug-a-bug.

252
00:20:31,329 --> 00:20:36,198
[Indistinct Chattering]

253
00:20:36,267 --> 00:20:38,531
- [Thomas] I've been wondering.
- [Julia] What is it, honey?

254
00:20:38,603 --> 00:20:42,801
How come I'm the only kid I know who
has invisible friends like you guys?

255
00:20:42,874 --> 00:20:46,105
Um, that's a very good
question, Thomas.

256
00:20:46,177 --> 00:20:49,544
- The Lord must have had some idea.
- I wish he'd let us in on it.

257
00:20:49,614 --> 00:20:53,641
- When I see him, I'll ask him.
- Hold up, Thomas, hold on.

258
00:20:53,718 --> 00:20:58,553
It's Miss Petersmann.
Oh, come on, baby, teach me somethin'.

259
00:20:59,891 --> 00:21:02,860
Oh, yes! Oh, no!

260
00:21:02,927 --> 00:21:05,487
- Damn!
- [Julia] We should have him neutered.

261
00:21:05,563 --> 00:21:09,932
And that is why we say...

262
00:21:10,001 --> 00:21:13,334
the battle of Gettysburg...

263
00:21:13,404 --> 00:21:18,034
was the most famous battle
of the Civil War.

264
00:21:19,878 --> 00:21:22,779
Any questions?

265
00:21:22,847 --> 00:21:25,680
Yes, Thomas. You have
something to add,

266
00:21:25,750 --> 00:21:27,684
- no doubt.
- Yes, ma'am.

267
00:21:27,752 --> 00:21:30,846
- With enthusiasm.
- Oh, I love it when
he tells it Harrison's way.

268
00:21:30,922 --> 00:21:32,856
- It's so much better.
- Thank you, Julia.

269
00:21:32,924 --> 00:21:35,449
The battle of Gettysburg.

270
00:21:35,527 --> 00:21:37,961
The third day.

271
00:21:38,029 --> 00:21:42,864
Pickett's charge.
The air hung heavily.

272
00:21:42,934 --> 00:21:45,637
- [Laughing]
- The acrid smell of gunpowder...

273
00:21:45,770 --> 00:21:49,206
and the stench
of the dead.

274
00:21:49,273 --> 00:21:52,504
- Ewww!
- Ooh-wa-ooh

275
00:21:52,577 --> 00:21:55,546
- Your own father said
give her up, don't bother
- Ooh-wa-ooh, ooh-wa-ooh

276
00:21:55,613 --> 00:21:58,605
- The world isn't coming to an end
- [Toilet Flushing]

277
00:21:58,683 --> 00:22:01,914
I'm gonna walk
like a man, yeah

278
00:22:01,986 --> 00:22:04,079
- Talk like a man
- Talk like a man, yeah

279
00:22:04,155 --> 00:22:07,750
Walk like a man
my son

280
00:22:07,825 --> 00:22:11,761
You know that no woman's worth
crawling on the earth

281
00:22:11,829 --> 00:22:15,526
So walk like a man
my son

282
00:22:15,600 --> 00:22:19,400
- My son
- Oooh

283
00:22:19,470 --> 00:22:23,429
[Thomas]
Down, down, down-down-down

284
00:22:23,508 --> 00:22:27,205
Down, down
down-down-down

285
00:22:27,278 --> 00:22:30,873
Down, down
down-down-down

286
00:22:30,948 --> 00:22:34,384
- Down, down, down-down-down
- [Bugle Fanfare]

287
00:22:34,452 --> 00:22:38,183
Silver Bullet in the fourth?
Buzz off, kid. This is for grown-ups.

288
00:22:38,256 --> 00:22:42,056
- Go buy a soda. Next? Hey, ki...
- Oh, please, mister.

289
00:22:42,126 --> 00:22:44,890
My dad said if I don't
place this bet for him,

290
00:22:44,962 --> 00:22:49,160
- I shouldn't come home ever.
- He'll give me an awful beating.

291
00:22:49,233 --> 00:22:52,202
He'll give me an awful beating.
[Crying]

292
00:22:53,504 --> 00:22:56,837
So please take my money.
Please! Okay?

293
00:22:56,908 --> 00:22:58,899
- Okay, okay.
- [Bell Rings]

294
00:22:58,976 --> 00:23:01,945
[Milo Shouting] I wanna win!
Let's go, let's go!

295
00:23:02,013 --> 00:23:04,641
- He's coming! Here he comes!
- Go, go, go!

296
00:23:04,716 --> 00:23:06,877
- He's gonna do it! Go, Silver Bullet!
- Go, go, go!

297
00:23:06,951 --> 00:23:08,942
Yes! Yes! Oh!

298
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:13,957
Does this little buckaroo know how
to pick a winner or what? Bam, bam.

299
00:23:14,025 --> 00:23:16,255
- [Drums]
- [Men Shouting] Go, go! Move!

300
00:23:16,327 --> 00:23:19,785
- You're outta here, ha-ha!
- Yes! That's how you move the ball.

301
00:23:19,864 --> 00:23:22,765
- Five more yards. This...
- That's exactly right. That's it.

302
00:23:22,834 --> 00:23:25,029
[Franco Corelli
Singing Opera]

303
00:23:25,103 --> 00:23:28,095
- Oh, it's so great.
- [Harrison] Right here, right here.

304
00:23:28,172 --> 00:23:31,903
Listen to this, the leitmotiv.
It's beautiful.

305
00:23:31,976 --> 00:23:36,276
Ooh, yeah, unbelievable.
Turn the page, Thomas. Turn the page.

306
00:23:36,347 --> 00:23:39,316
Okay, fold that out
for me.

307
00:23:39,383 --> 00:23:43,285
Oh. Oh, mounds of joy.

308
00:23:43,354 --> 00:23:46,653
Hey, could we muzzle
this Mario Lanza guy?

309
00:23:46,724 --> 00:23:49,420
It's Franco Corelli, for God's sakes!
You absorb nothing.

310
00:23:49,494 --> 00:23:53,487
- Whatever!
- Hold that page a second.

311
00:23:55,500 --> 00:23:58,230
[Penny]
My Billy is 11 years old today.

312
00:23:58,302 --> 00:24:01,931
Wherever those kids are,
I'm sure they're safe...

313
00:24:02,006 --> 00:24:07,137
- and happy.
- I just wish I knew.

314
00:24:07,211 --> 00:24:11,705
You still think about John,
don't you?

315
00:24:11,783 --> 00:24:15,344
Every day.

316
00:24:15,419 --> 00:24:17,853
Sweetie. Mmm.

317
00:24:23,361 --> 00:24:26,455
Let's go get the guys.

318
00:24:26,531 --> 00:24:29,091
- [Laughing]
- [Laughing]

319
00:24:29,167 --> 00:24:33,661
[Franco Corelli
Singing Continues]

320
00:24:33,738 --> 00:24:35,968
Why don't you boys come up
and see the sunset?

321
00:24:38,242 --> 00:24:40,142
Harrison.

322
00:24:40,211 --> 00:24:43,408
- What?
- We're listening to Franco Corelli.

323
00:24:43,481 --> 00:24:45,449
- The leitmotiv.
- Yeah.

324
00:24:47,251 --> 00:24:50,584
[Ice Cream Truck]

325
00:24:58,196 --> 00:25:00,130
- Mr. Reilly?
- Yes.

326
00:25:00,198 --> 00:25:03,395
Charles Polito,
Child Welfare Department.

327
00:25:03,467 --> 00:25:05,731
Neither of you
bets on the horses?

328
00:25:05,803 --> 00:25:08,033
- I've never even been to a horse race.
- No.

329
00:25:08,105 --> 00:25:10,039
You... Talk to anyone
who knows me.

330
00:25:11,375 --> 00:25:14,503
Well, your son has been
seen at the track.

331
00:25:14,579 --> 00:25:16,877
He's telling the story...

332
00:25:16,948 --> 00:25:20,884
that you will give him a beating
if he doesn't place your bets.

333
00:25:22,954 --> 00:25:26,412
[Thunder Rumbling]

334
00:25:26,490 --> 00:25:28,924
[Eva] How could you
even think it?

335
00:25:28,993 --> 00:25:31,325
We are not putting our son
in some mental hospital!

336
00:25:31,395 --> 00:25:34,330
Oh, Eva!
No one is saying that.

337
00:25:34,398 --> 00:25:37,731
Dr. Beecham is a child psychiatrist.
He's just gonna do some tests.

338
00:25:37,802 --> 00:25:41,067
- Tests?
- Therapy, tests, whatever it is!

339
00:25:41,138 --> 00:25:44,699
Everyone says he needs help.
The guy from child welfare, his teacher.

340
00:25:44,775 --> 00:25:48,677
That old battle-ax has no idea how to
handle a precocious child like Thomas.

341
00:25:48,746 --> 00:25:53,513
Thomas has a serious problem. He blames
everything on these imaginary people!

342
00:25:53,584 --> 00:25:56,917
I've been saying for years we should
get him proper care, and you know it!

343
00:25:56,988 --> 00:26:00,788
- Because he has a vivid imagination?
- Stop living in a fantasy world.

344
00:26:00,858 --> 00:26:05,420
You can't continue that.
You can't play his little games!

345
00:26:05,563 --> 00:26:07,929
[Rain Falling]

346
00:26:09,834 --> 00:26:12,302
[Thunder Rumbling]

347
00:26:14,772 --> 00:26:17,206
Not one of you knows
what it's like to lose a child.

348
00:26:17,275 --> 00:26:19,766
I lost three.
I'm not losing Thomas.

349
00:26:19,844 --> 00:26:23,075
Penny, look what's going on here.
This is wrong.

350
00:26:23,147 --> 00:26:25,615
Yeah, it's gotten
way out of hand.

351
00:26:25,683 --> 00:26:29,710
Maybe we were never supposed to
talk to him or even let him see us.

352
00:26:29,787 --> 00:26:32,449
Hey, come on.

353
00:26:32,523 --> 00:26:36,118
We can't just go invisible on the kid.
It's stupid!

354
00:26:36,193 --> 00:26:39,788
[Sighing] He's gonna hate us,
I'm tellin' you.

355
00:26:39,864 --> 00:26:43,061
- Julia, we're his family.
- No, we're not his family.

356
00:26:43,134 --> 00:26:47,070
We're...
I don't know what we are.

357
00:26:47,138 --> 00:26:51,006
He's got a mother and a father.
We've gotta let them be his parents.

358
00:26:51,075 --> 00:26:53,771
Leavin' Thomas would be
like dyin' all over again.

359
00:26:53,844 --> 00:26:56,642
Penny...

360
00:26:56,714 --> 00:27:00,673
I never had
any children...

361
00:27:00,751 --> 00:27:05,552
but for a little while
with Thomas...

362
00:27:05,623 --> 00:27:08,251
I got to feel like a father.

363
00:27:08,326 --> 00:27:10,521
This isn't easy for any of us.

364
00:27:10,594 --> 00:27:12,789
Now... Just wait.

365
00:27:12,863 --> 00:27:17,800
Now, if we're so bad for Thomas, how
come we're stuck to him? Tell me that.

366
00:27:17,868 --> 00:27:20,462
We don't know, okay?

367
00:27:20,538 --> 00:27:24,838
So, what? What, we don't
let him see us or hear us?

368
00:27:26,210 --> 00:27:28,735
What, we never even
talk to him?

369
00:27:28,813 --> 00:27:31,509
We just... hang around?

370
00:27:31,582 --> 00:27:35,211
Watch him for the rest
of his life?

371
00:27:35,286 --> 00:27:37,652
What, like
a bunch of ghosts?

372
00:27:39,924 --> 00:27:44,384
- That's gonna be hell.
- Maybe that's what this is, Milo.

373
00:27:49,633 --> 00:27:52,796
- Well, I guess we better
wake him up and say good-bye.
- Wait!

374
00:27:52,870 --> 00:27:54,861
Thomas. Thomas.

375
00:27:54,939 --> 00:27:58,705
- Sweetie, Thomas?
- What?

376
00:27:58,776 --> 00:28:01,973
Oh, goodness,
you are such a big boy.

377
00:28:02,046 --> 00:28:03,946
[Harrison]
We love you, Thomas.

378
00:28:04,015 --> 00:28:07,473
I love you too.

379
00:28:07,551 --> 00:28:10,281
Thomas, you know
how we've always said...

380
00:28:10,354 --> 00:28:12,788
we didn't know how long
we were gonna be with you?

381
00:28:12,857 --> 00:28:14,484
Yes.

382
00:28:14,558 --> 00:28:17,994
Well... um...

383
00:28:18,062 --> 00:28:21,725
It's time for you
to be like other kids.

384
00:28:21,799 --> 00:28:24,393
Just be with your mommy
and your daddy.

385
00:28:24,468 --> 00:28:29,235
Thomas, we feel the time
has come for us to go away.

386
00:28:29,306 --> 00:28:31,240
What? No!

387
00:28:31,308 --> 00:28:35,244
Yeah, buddy.
It'll be a lot better for ya.

388
00:28:35,312 --> 00:28:38,748
- Honest.
- We don't want to, but we have to go.

389
00:28:38,816 --> 00:28:41,410
No, please!
I'll do anything you want.

390
00:28:41,485 --> 00:28:44,977
I'll pretend you're not there,
okay? It will be a secret.

391
00:28:45,056 --> 00:28:47,752
Oh, we can't do that, sweetie.
It doesn't work.

392
00:28:47,825 --> 00:28:50,988
Don't cry. We're gonna be right here
watchin' over you.

393
00:28:51,062 --> 00:28:53,257
Just quietly.

394
00:28:53,330 --> 00:28:55,821
You'll be okay, kiddo.

395
00:28:55,900 --> 00:28:58,926
You'll grow up,
forget about us.

396
00:28:59,003 --> 00:29:00,994
No, I won't. I won't!

397
00:29:04,475 --> 00:29:08,571
- So long, buckaroo.
- Come back. Don't leave me!

398
00:29:08,646 --> 00:29:11,547
Milo!

399
00:29:11,615 --> 00:29:13,810
I'm so sorry, Thomas.

400
00:29:13,884 --> 00:29:16,819
[Crying]

401
00:29:19,190 --> 00:29:23,126
You said you were my special friends,
and special friends don't go away.

402
00:29:23,194 --> 00:29:25,128
[Julia] You're gonna
find new friends.

403
00:29:25,196 --> 00:29:28,097
You certainly will.
You are a great guy.

404
00:29:28,165 --> 00:29:31,498
I don't want new friends.
I want you.

405
00:29:33,437 --> 00:29:35,337
[Crying Continues]

406
00:29:37,007 --> 00:29:39,805
I just wish I could
give you a big hug.

407
00:29:39,877 --> 00:29:43,074
- Julia!
- Good-bye, Sweetie.

408
00:29:43,147 --> 00:29:47,106
- I love you.
- I love you.

409
00:29:47,184 --> 00:29:48,486
Come back.

410
00:29:48,486 --> 00:29:49,453
Come back.

411
00:29:51,722 --> 00:29:55,453
[Crying Continues]

412
00:29:55,526 --> 00:29:57,460
Good-bye, Thomas.

413
00:29:57,528 --> 00:30:01,123
Please stay!
Ohhh!

414
00:30:01,198 --> 00:30:03,166
Harrison!

415
00:30:03,234 --> 00:30:05,225
- Thomas.
- Huh?

416
00:30:09,006 --> 00:30:11,975
I am so proud of you.

417
00:30:12,042 --> 00:30:15,569
Don't go. Penny.

418
00:30:15,646 --> 00:30:18,911
Thomas, no worries.

419
00:30:18,983 --> 00:30:21,213
I need you.

420
00:30:21,285 --> 00:30:25,244
Just come back, come back!

421
00:30:25,322 --> 00:30:28,348
Come back, don't go!

422
00:30:29,426 --> 00:30:32,623
Don't go, come back!

423
00:30:32,696 --> 00:30:36,029
Milo! Julia!

424
00:30:36,100 --> 00:30:40,196
Harrison!
[Crying Continues]

425
00:30:44,074 --> 00:30:47,635
Julia! Harrison!

426
00:30:50,514 --> 00:30:53,915
Penny! Milo!

427
00:30:54,018 --> 00:30:57,920
[Crying Continues]

428
00:31:08,165 --> 00:31:10,099
[Harrison] "I have a nice pair
of 100% wool socks.

429
00:31:10,167 --> 00:31:12,101
I don't think
they're gonna bother you."

430
00:31:12,169 --> 00:31:15,661
I said, "You're telling me what's
gonna bother me, what I'm allergic to."

431
00:31:15,739 --> 00:31:18,902
- So I ended up getting a dozen pairs...
- Pairs, 25% nylon.

432
00:31:18,976 --> 00:31:23,106
- Have I told you this before?
- When Thomas was about 15.

433
00:31:24,682 --> 00:31:26,616
[Milo]
Where are we, anyway?

434
00:31:26,684 --> 00:31:30,711
Stellar Aviation. Another bankruptcy.
Don't you ever pay attention?

435
00:31:30,788 --> 00:31:33,586
[Penny] I wonder why they
always send Thomas to do this.

436
00:31:33,657 --> 00:31:37,787
- 'Cause it doesn't seem to bother him.
- It does.

437
00:31:37,861 --> 00:31:39,795
- [Tools Drilling]
- Ohh.

438
00:31:39,863 --> 00:31:43,856
- Stop it. You're never gonna catch one.
- [Sighs]

439
00:31:45,669 --> 00:31:49,298
- Hey, look, I'm a man.
- You're a dead man.

440
00:31:49,373 --> 00:31:53,241
You bug my ass. You've been
buggin' my ass since the early '70s.

441
00:31:53,310 --> 00:31:56,245
- This guy chose it.
- [Thomas] Patterson, how you doin'?

442
00:31:56,313 --> 00:31:59,407
Use the same damn parts
if you got to, but get going.

443
00:31:59,483 --> 00:32:02,145
- Dreyfuss!
- Patterson, where you been?

444
00:32:02,219 --> 00:32:04,483
- What are you trying to do, Mr. Reilly?
- I'm trying to contact you.

445
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:06,785
I phoned, I faxed, I messengered,
I paged. You're very mysterious.

446
00:32:06,857 --> 00:32:09,348
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
So get to the point, huh?

447
00:32:09,426 --> 00:32:12,020
[Sighing] You're aware of
the bankruptcy hearing on Monday?

448
00:32:12,096 --> 00:32:14,257
- Yes, of course I'm aware of it.
- Okay. Well,

449
00:32:14,331 --> 00:32:17,823
I just dropped by to tell you my bank...
actually, the rest of your creditors...

450
00:32:17,901 --> 00:32:20,199
have decided to push
for liquidation.

451
00:32:20,270 --> 00:32:23,137
- What?
- [Equipment Drilling Continues]

452
00:32:23,207 --> 00:32:26,404
Look, I'm not bankrupt.
I'm just behind a little.

453
00:32:26,477 --> 00:32:31,141
A little behind,
6.4 million, $6,429,089.

454
00:32:31,215 --> 00:32:35,914
We're gonna reorganize under chapter 11,
so it's gonna take some time.

455
00:32:35,986 --> 00:32:40,480
So you and the others are just
gonna have to wait for your money.

456
00:32:40,557 --> 00:32:42,821
See, we have waited,

457
00:32:42,893 --> 00:32:47,455
and we've watched you drain
more money out of this company.

458
00:32:47,531 --> 00:32:50,295
Think you can
take me on, Reilly?

459
00:32:50,367 --> 00:32:54,326
If you think you have
a case for reorganization,

